erilisfrm58.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=635.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Paying for report cards/grades</span><hr size=1> voted for<br>&quot;Don't pay for grades, it doesn't teach kids to do well to feel good.&quot;<br><br>&gt;&gt; it's really sad when their motivation to do well is because of some money.<br>&gt;&gt; besides when they get to highschool those money will mean very little to them<br><br>I wish i had the answer to motivate kids, but I guess until they realize they are doing it for themselves they won't get good grades. <p><hr><center>57 monk of Brell Serilis<br>~I am gone, long gone~<br><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=74782>Magelo Profile</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#403C50><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uroguemotoko.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rogue Motoko</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/31/02 1:43:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisfrm58.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=635.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Getting paid for grades</span><hr size=1> I used to get some money for a good report back when I was in basic education.  It was about 3 dollars for the whole thing. <br><br>In high school my parents would give allowance according to my Grades, where they good I got more, where they bad I got less.  Where they horrible I would get nothing untill the next report.   <br><br>I spend one period without any cash, enough to say that that never happened a second time.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#464446><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uaelnelda.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aelnelda</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.aelf.net/pics/eye-sig.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Artist</span><br>  Posts: 320<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/31/02 2:14:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisfrm58.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=635.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.aelf.net/pics/ael-pic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Getting paid for grades</span><hr size=1> I don't think it was heard of to give money for good reports when I was at school, well I guess only amongst the rich (nose in the air) kids - they got pocket money for doing nothing!<br><br>The thing that I remember about getting good grades was the presentation of certificates by the school.<br><br>I did get a summer bonus (money) for passing my exams, both from my parents and grandparents, but then most people did, I suppose. Either that or we went out for a meal or some other treat like that. I'm trying to think back to see if it had any influence on me, but I can't honestly remember. I know I set my own goals and it was nice to get a reward for doing my best, as my goals were much higher than I was probably capable of.<br><br>I guess what I valued the most was that my parents knew I tried hard at school work and would be happy whatever marks I got, so long as I tried. I knew they couldn't afford to do what some parents did, and there were three of us kids!<br> <p><table width="340" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">  <tr>     <td colspan="3"><img src="http://www.aelf.net/pics/aels-sig.gif" width="340" height="150"></td>  </tr>  <tr>     <td><a href="mailto:email@aelf.net"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="1">email       me</font></a></td>    <td>       <div align="center"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="1"><a href="http://www.aelf.net" target="_blank">www.aelf.net</a></font></div>    </td>    <td>       <div align="right"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="1"><a href="http://www.aelf.net/legend" target="_blank">Legend         Ward</a></font></div>    </td>  </tr></table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#403C50><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukhorenstonefall.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Khoren Stonefall</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_magentaspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elven Lovepony</span><br>  Posts: 1267<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/31/02 6:47:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisfrm58.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=635.topic&index=5>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/jmlong/khoren_little.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Getting paid for grades</span><hr size=1> I voted for the first option--go ahead and do it.  If you do it properly, it should be a positive experience on a bunch of levels.  <br><br>First, it's a reality in life that many rewards are based on performance, and this can be a really important motivator for certain people in certain situations.  It is not always enough to do something well just for the self-satisfaction of having done it well.  If all motivation came down to that, people would learn that if they don't find something satisfying, they may as well abdicate responsibility for doing it.  As important as it is to teach someone to have pride and do well for their own sake, it's also important to teach them that there are rewards for excelling at tasks we don't like, or in which we do not see intrinsic value.  We do not always find ourselves in our ideal careers or in our ideal circumstances of self-realization.  I would not have come to work this morning if they weren't paying me, but sometimes we have to do what must be done.  Ideally, I would want my kids to feel connected to the labour/reward process so they learn to have a vested interest in not being lazy, rather than a vague moral sense that they shouldn't be.<br><br>But secondly, and more importantly, I think the financial reward, if you're enthusiastic about it, is a great vehicle for showing you're involved and interested in what they're doing, and that their success inspires your praise, generosity, and reward all at the same time.  If the process becomes a formality, where you count up the X's and grudgingly hand over the cash, then it'll totally fail to be a positive experience, but if you can get across that magic sense that you care, and that because you're proud you're happy to keep your generous side of the bargain, you've rolled praise and positive reinforcement (which helps teach to take pride in good work), and a sense that working at something inspires reward and generosity (which helps teach not to be lazy when pride alone isn't enough--for example, in situations where posting on message boards seems more worthwhile than doing what I'm paid for) all into one.<br><br>My parents never gave me any financial reward for my report cards, either, but from what I can remember, they tended to buy me things, rather than give me the money to buy them myself, so if they wanted to reward me for something like a report card, they'd probably have done it in a less measurable fashion than you've described above.  Anyway, there's lots of ways to teach the same lessons.  This one just seems as good as many alternatives.<br><br>Khoren Stonefall<br>Level 60 Crusader of Marr<br>Silent Redemption <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#464446><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/unasteratuofbrell.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nasteratu of Brell</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>P'diddy's man servant</span><br>  Posts: 833<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/31/02 8:43:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisfrm58.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=635.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Getting paid for grades</span><hr size=1> I agree w/ Khoren, the paying for grades system worked for me. Its just how you set it up, set a limit like X$ for a B and 2X$ for an A, nothing for a C because C is average and you are paying for above average work. Along with teaching kids the reward for work it can also teach them how to spend and budget their money. Insted of buying them somthing just tell them to save the money that they earned from their grades. This will encourage not only saving money but also getting better grades to recieve more money so they can attain their desired item faster. <p><p align=center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=55580"><img src="http://home.nycap.rr.com/azire/nasteratu.jpg"></a><BR><i>(un)</i>Retired 60 Slackromancer of Brell<br><b>The perfect compliment to your cleric</b><br><b><a href="http:\\www.legionofheroes.org">Legion of Heroes</a></b><BR></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#403C50><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubloohsugah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>BloohSugah</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://blooh.5u.com/u032.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I DEMAND!<br>I'm a little demander!</span><br>  Posts: 362<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(1/31/02 10:30:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fbrellserilisfrm58.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=635.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Getting paid for grades</span><hr size=1> My kids get to pick out a toy if they 